# OmniStock — environment variable shape contract (F-000 · T-000-02).
# Spec: docs/features/F-000/infra.md §8.1. This is the SHAPE contract, not a
# credential source — every value below is a placeholder. Copy to `.env`
# (gitignored) and adjust for your machine before running `apps/api`.
#
# Validated at boot by the zod schema in packages/config/src/env.ts (AC14).

# --- Database (Postgres, via docker-compose "postgres" service) -------------
DATABASE_URL="postgresql://omnistock:omnistock@localhost:5432/omnistock_dev?schema=public"

# --- Redis (via docker-compose "redis" service; consumed by BullMQ, T-000-08) -
REDIS_URL="redis://localhost:6379"

# --- Auth (placeholders — real secrets are never committed) -----------------
# Must be >=32 chars (256-bit random) and the two values must differ — enforced
# by the zod schema (F-001 I-4). These are still non-secret dev placeholders;
# generate real random values for any shared/deployed environment (@devops).
JWT_ACCESS_SECRET="dev-access-secret-change-me-0000000000"
JWT_REFRESH_SECRET="dev-refresh-secret-change-me-0000000000"

# --- Runtime ------------------------------------------------------------------
PORT="3000"
NODE_ENV="development"

# --- Web dev proxy target (F-001 T-001-11, apps/web/next.config.mjs) ---------
# Same-origin dev proxy: apps/web rewrites `/api/*` to this API origin so the
# browser only ever talks to its own origin (avoids SameSite=None + CORS
# entirely in dev; SameSite=Strict behaves as it will in prod). Only read by
# apps/web's Next config, not by apps/api.
API_ORIGIN="http://localhost:3000"

# --- Dev-CORS + cookie credentials (F-001 T-001-11) --------------------------
# Spec: docs/features/F-001/architecture.md §12, api-spec.md §0 ("Dev-CORS").
# Comma-separated allow-list of browser origins the API may set
# `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` + `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true` for
# (needed only when the browser calls the API cross-origin with the
# `omni_rt`/`omni_csrf` cookies attached — SameSite=Strict + credentials:true
# requires an explicit origin, never `*`). In the normal local-dev flow the
# Next.js dev server proxies `/api/*` to the API via rewrites (see
# apps/web/next.config.mjs), so the browser sees same-origin requests and this
# list is not exercised — it exists as a fallback for direct cross-origin dev
# setups (e.g. hitting the API from a non-proxied port) and is NOT used in
# prod (prod is same-site; SameSite=Strict is the only cookie scope needed).
# apps/api (backend-api, T-001-07) reads this to configure NestJS `enableCors`.
CORS_ALLOWED_ORIGINS="http://localhost:3001"

# --- Trusted-proxy real client IP (F-001 T-001-12) ----------------------------
# Spec: docs/features/F-001/architecture.md §8.3, §12.
# `X-Forwarded-For` must only be honored when the immediate connecting peer is
# a KNOWN proxy/load-balancer — otherwise a raw client can spoof the header
# and bypass the IP-throttle (arch §8.1). Two knobs:
#   - TRUST_PROXY_HOPS: how many hops of X-Forwarded-For to trust, counting
#     from the right (Express/NestJS `app.set('trust proxy', N)` semantics).
#     Local dev / single-instance deploys with no proxy in front: "0" (the
#     socket's remote address IS the client — never trust any XFF hop).
#     Behind exactly one reverse proxy/load balancer (typical single-region
#     prod): "1". Raise only if a real additional hop is added (e.g. CDN in
#     front of the LB) — never set higher than the actual known chain length.
#   - TRUSTED_PROXY_IPS: optional comma-separated allow-list of the proxy's
#     own IP(s)/CIDR ranges, for defense-in-depth when the runtime supports an
#     IP-based trust check (e.g. a PaaS load balancer with a stable egress
#     range) in addition to the hop count. Empty = rely on TRUST_PROXY_HOPS
#     alone (acceptable for MVP single-proxy topologies).
# TLS assumption (architecture.md §9 "Transport"): TLS terminates AT the
# trusted proxy/load balancer, never at the API instance directly from the
# public internet — the API trusts `X-Forwarded-Proto`/client-IP forwarding
# only because the hop in front of it is a proxy WE operate and terminate TLS
# on, not an arbitrary intermediary. apps/api (backend-api, T-001-06/T-001-07)
# reads these to configure Express's trust-proxy setting before the throttle
# middleware derives the client IP.
TRUST_PROXY_HOPS="1"
TRUSTED_PROXY_IPS=""
